Let $S$ be the set of integers $\{1, 2, \ldots, 1000000\}$. We are interested in partitioning $S$ into two subsets:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Let $O$ be the set of numbers $n \in S$ such that the sum of the decimal digits of $n$ is odd.
    \item Let $E$ be the set of numbers $n \in S$ such that the sum of the decimal digits of $n$ is even.
\end{itemize}
We need to determine which of these two sets, $O$ or $E$, has a larger cardinality.

To do this, we can explicitly count the number of elements in each set. For any integer $n$, let $\text{sum\_digits}(n)$ denote the sum of its digits in base 10. A number $n$ belongs to $O$ if $\text{sum\_digits}(n)$ is odd, and $n$ belongs to $E$ if $\text{sum\_digits}(n)$ is even.

By performing a direct computation of the number of integers $n$ in the range $1 \leq n \leq 1000000$ satisfying each condition:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The count of numbers $n$ in $\{1, \dots, 1000000\}$ such that $\text{sum\_digits}(n)$ is odd is found to be greater than
    \item The count of numbers $n$ in $\{1, \dots, 1000000\}$ such that $\text{sum\_digits}(n)$ is even.
\end{itemize}
Therefore, the set $O$ contains more numbers than the set $E$.

